[src:knapsack-dp/change-making-problem] The **change-making problem** addresses the question of finding the minimum number of coins (of certain denominations) that add up to a given amount of money.
[src:knapsack-dp/change-making-problem] It is a special case of the integer knapsack problem, and has applications wider than just currency.
[src:knapsack-dp/change-making-problem] It is weakly NP-hard, but may be solved optimally in pseudo-polynomial time by dynamic programming.
[src:knapsack-dp/change-making-problem] Coin values can be modeled by a set of n distinct positive integer values (whole numbers), arranged in increasing order as *w*1 through *w**n*.
[src:knapsack-dp/change-making-problem] An application of change-making problem can be found in computing the ways one can make a nine dart finish in a game of darts.
[src:knapsack-dp/change-making-problem] Another application is computing the possible atomic (or isotopic) composition of a given mass/charge peak in mass spectrometry.
[src:knapsack-dp/change-making-problem] A classic dynamic programming strategy works upward by finding the combinations of all smaller values that would sum to the current threshold.
[src:knapsack-dp/change-making-problem] Thus, at each threshold, all previous thresholds are potentially considered to work upward to the goal amount *W*.
[src:knapsack-dp/change-making-problem] For this reason, this dynamic programming approach requires a number of steps that is O(*nW),* where *n* is the number of types of coins.
[src:knapsack-dp/change-making-problem] The following is a dynamic programming implementation (with Python 3) which uses a matrix to keep track of the optimal solutions to sub-problems, and returns the minimum number of coins, or "Infinity" if there is no way to make change with the coins given.
[src:knapsack-dp/change-making-problem] A second matrix may be used to obtain the set of coins for the optimal solution.
[src:knapsack-dp/change-making-problem] For many real-world coin systems, such as those used in the US and many other countries, a greedy algorithm of picking the largest denomination of coin which is not greater than the remaining amount to be made will produce the optimal result.
[src:knapsack-dp/change-making-problem] This is not the case for arbitrary coin systems or even some real world systems, though.
[src:knapsack-dp/change-making-problem] For instance, if we consider the old (now withdrawn) Indian coin denominations of 5, 10, 20 and 25 paise, then to make 40 paise, the greedy algorithm would choose three coins (25, 10, 5) whereas the optimal solution is two coins (20, 20).
[src:knapsack-dp/change-making-problem] Another example is attempting to make 40 US cents without nickels (denomination 25, 10, 1) with similar result — the greedy chooses seven coins (25, 10, and 5 × 1), but the optimal is four (4 × 10).
[src:knapsack-dp/change-making-problem] A coin system is called "canonical" if the greedy algorithm always solves its change-making problem optimally.
[src:knapsack-dp/change-making-problem] It is possible to test whether a coin system is canonical in polynomial time.
[src:knapsack-dp/change-making-problem] The "optimal denomination problem" is a problem for people who design entirely new currencies.
[src:knapsack-dp/change-making-problem] It asks what denominations should be chosen for the coins in order to minimize the average cost of making change, that is, the average number of coins needed to make change.
[src:knapsack-dp/change-making-problem] The version of this problem assumed that the people making change will use the minimum number of coins (from the denominations available).
[src:knapsack-dp/change-making-problem] One variation of this problem assumes that the people making change will use the "greedy algorithm" for making change, even when that requires more than the minimum number of coins.
[src:knapsack-dp/change-making-problem] Most current currencies use a 1-2-5 series, but some other set of denominations would require fewer denominations of coins or a smaller average number of coins to make change or both.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] In both contexts it refers to simplifying a complicated problem by breaking it down into simpler sub-problems in a recursive manner.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] While some decision problems cannot be taken apart this way, decisions that span several points in time do often break apart recursively.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Likewise, in computer science, if a problem can be solved optimally by breaking it into sub-problems and then recursively finding the optimal solutions to the sub-problems, then it is said to have *optimal substructure*.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] If sub-problems can be nested recursively inside larger problems, so that dynamic programming methods are applicable, then there is a relation between the value of the larger problem and the values of the sub-problems.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] In the optimization literature this relationship is called the Bellman equation.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] In terms of mathematical optimization, dynamic programming usually refers to simplifying a decision by breaking it down into a sequence of decision steps over time.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] This is done by defining a sequence of **value functions** *V*1, *V*2, ..., *V**n* taking *y* as an argument representing the **state** of the system at times *i* from 1 to *n*.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] The definition of *V**n*(*y*) is the value obtained in state *y* at the last time *n*.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] The values *V**i* at earlier times *i* = *n* −1, *n* − 2, ..., 2, 1 can be found by working backwards, using a recursive relationship called the Bellman equation.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] For *i* = 2, ..., *n*, *V**i*−1 at any state *y* is calculated from *V**i* by maximizing a simple function (usually the sum) of the gain from a decision at time *i* − 1 and the function *V**i* at the new state of the system if this decision is made.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Since *V**i* has already been calculated for the needed states, the above operation yields *V**i*−1 for those states.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Finally, *V*1 at the initial state of the system is the value of the optimal solution.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] The optimal values of the decision variables can be recovered, one by one, by tracking back the calculations already performed.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] The solution to this problem is an optimal control law or policy $\mathbf {u} ^{\ast }=h(\mathbf {x} (t),t)$ , which produces an optimal trajectory $\mathbf {x} ^{\ast }$ and a cost-to-go function $J^{\ast }$ .
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] In practice, this generally requires numerical techniques for some discrete approximation to the exact optimization relationship.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] at the k -th stage of n equally spaced discrete time intervals, and where ${\hat {f}}$ and ${\hat {\mathbf {g} }}$ denote discrete approximations to f and $\mathbf {g}$ .
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] This functional equation is known as the Bellman equation, which can be solved for an exact solution of the discrete approximation of the optimization equation.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] In economics, the objective is generally to maximize (rather than minimize) some dynamic social welfare function.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] In Ramsey's problem, this function relates amounts of consumption to levels of utility.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Loosely speaking, the planner faces the trade-off between contemporaneous consumption and future consumption (via investment in capital stock that is used in production), known as intertemporal choice.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Future consumption is discounted at a constant rate $\beta \in (0,1)$ .
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] where c is consumption, k is capital, and f is a production function satisfying the Inada conditions.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] An initial capital stock $k_{0}>0$ is assumed.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Let $c_{t}$ be consumption in period t, and assume consumption yields utility $u(c_{t})=\ln(c_{t})$ as long as the consumer lives.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Assume the consumer is impatient, so that he discounts future utility by a factor b each period, where $0<b<1$ .
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Assume initial capital is a given amount $k_{0}>0$ , and suppose that this period's capital and consumption determine next period's capital as $k_{t+1}=Ak_{t}^{a}-c_{t}$ , where A is a positive constant and $0<a<1$ .
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Written this way, the problem looks complicated, because it involves solving for all the choice variables $c_{0},c_{1},c_{2},\ldots ,c_{T}$ .
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] The dynamic programming approach to solve this problem involves breaking it apart into a sequence of smaller decisions.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] To do so, we define a sequence of *value functions* $V_{t}(k)$ , for $t=0,1,2,\ldots ,T,T+1$ which represent the value of having any amount of capital k at each time t.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] There is (by assumption) no utility from having capital after death, $V_{T+1}(k)=0$ .
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] The value of any quantity of capital at any previous time can be calculated by backward induction using the Bellman equation.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] This problem is much simpler than the one we wrote down before, because it involves only two decision variables, $c_{t}$ and $k_{t+1}$ .
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Intuitively, instead of choosing his whole lifetime plan at birth, the consumer can take things one step at a time.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] At time t, his current capital $k_{t}$ is given, and he only needs to choose current consumption $c_{t}$ and saving $k_{t+1}$ .
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] To actually solve this problem, we work backwards.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] For simplicity, the current level of capital is denoted as k. $V_{T+1}(k)$ is already known, so using the Bellman equation once we can calculate $V_{T}(k)$ , and so on until we get to $V_{0}(k)$ , which is the *value* of the initial decision problem for the whole lifetime.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] We see that it is optimal to consume a larger fraction of current wealth as one gets older, finally consuming all remaining wealth in period T, the last period of life.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] There are two key attributes that a problem must have in order for dynamic programming to be applicable: optimal substructure and overlapping sub-problems.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] If a problem can be solved by combining optimal solutions to *non-overlapping* sub-problems, the strategy is called "divide and conquer" instead.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] This is why merge sort and quick sort are not classified as dynamic programming problems.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Some programming languages can automatically memoize the result of a function call with a particular set of arguments, in order to speed up call-by-name evaluation (this mechanism is referred to as *call-by-need*).
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Some languages make it possible portably (e.g.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Some languages have automatic memoization built in, such as tabled Prolog and J, which supports memoization with the *M.* adverb.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] In any case, this is only possible for a referentially transparent function.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Memoization is also encountered as an easily accessible design pattern within term-rewrite based languages such as Wolfram Language.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Dynamic programming is widely used in bioinformatics for tasks such as sequence alignment, protein folding, RNA structure prediction and protein-DNA binding.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] The first dynamic programming algorithms for protein-DNA binding were developed in the 1970s independently by Charles DeLisi in the US and by Georgii Gurskii and Alexander Zasedatelev in the Soviet Union.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Recently these algorithms have become very popular in bioinformatics and computational biology, particularly in the studies of nucleosome positioning and transcription factor binding.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] From a dynamic programming point of view, Dijkstra's algorithm for the shortest path problem is a successive approximation scheme that solves the dynamic programming functional equation for the shortest path problem by the **Reaching** method.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] is a paraphrasing of Bellman's famous Principle of Optimality in the context of the shortest path problem.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Using dynamic programming in the calculation of the *n*th member of the Fibonacci sequence improves its performance greatly.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] In particular, `fib(2)` was calculated three times from scratch.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] In larger examples, many more values of `fib`, or *subproblems*, are recalculated, leading to an exponential time algorithm.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Now, suppose we have a simple map object, *m*, which maps each value of `fib` that has already been calculated to its result, and we modify our function to use it and update it.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] This technique of saving values that have already been calculated is called *memoization*; this is the top-down approach, since we first break the problem into subproblems and then calculate and store values.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] In the **bottom-up** approach, we calculate the smaller values of `fib` first, then build larger values from them.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] This method also uses O(*n*) time since it contains a loop that repeats n − 1 times, but it only takes constant (O(1)) space, in contrast to the top-down approach which requires O(*n*) space to store the map.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] In both examples, we only calculate `fib(2)` one time, and then use it to calculate both `fib(4)` and `fib(3)`, instead of computing it every time either of them is evaluated.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Consider the problem of assigning values, either zero or one, to the positions of an *n* × *n* matrix, with *n* even, so that each row and each column contains exactly *n* / 2 zeros and *n* / 2 ones.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] We ask how many different assignments there are for a given n.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] There are at least three possible approaches: brute force, backtracking, and dynamic programming.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Brute force consists of checking all assignments of zeros and ones and counting those that have balanced rows and columns (*n* / 2 zeros and *n* / 2 ones).
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] As there are $2^{n^{2}}$ possible assignments and ${\tbinom {n}{n/2}}^{n}$ sensible assignments, this strategy is not practical for arbitrarily large values of n .
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Backtracking for this problem consists of choosing some order of the matrix elements and recursively placing ones or zeros, while checking that in every row and column the number of elements that have not been assigned plus the number of ones or zeros are both at least *n* / 2.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] While more sophisticated than brute force, this approach will visit every solution once, making it impractical for *n* larger than six, since the number of solutions is already 116963796250 for *n* = 8, as we shall see.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Dynamic programming makes it possible to count the number of solutions without visiting them all.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Imagine backtracking values for the first row – what information would we require about the remaining rows, in order to be able to accurately count the solutions obtained for each first row value?
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] We consider *k* × *n* boards, where 1 ≤ *k* ≤ *n*, whose k rows contain $n/2$ zeros and $n/2$ ones.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] The function *f* to which memoization is applied maps vectors of *n* pairs of integers to the number of admissible boards (solutions).
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] There is one pair for each column, and its two components indicate respectively the number of zeros and ones that have yet to be placed in that column.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] If any one of the results is negative, then the assignment is invalid and does not contribute to the set of solutions (recursion stops).
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Otherwise, we have an assignment for the top row of the *k* × *n* board and recursively compute the number of solutions to the remaining (*k* − 1) × *n* board, adding the numbers of solutions for every admissible assignment of the top row and returning the sum, which is being memoized.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] The base case is the trivial subproblem, which occurs for a 1 × *n* board.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] The number of solutions for this board is either zero or one, depending on whether the vector is a permutation of *n* / 2 (0, 1) and *n* / 2 (1, 0) pairs or not.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Links to the MAPLE implementation of the dynamic programming approach may be found among the external links.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Consider a checkerboard with *n* × *n* squares and a cost function `c(i, j)` which returns a cost associated with square `(i,j)` (`*i*` being the row, `*j*` being the column).
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] This problem exhibits **optimal substructure**.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] That is, the solution to the entire problem relies on solutions to subproblems.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Starting at rank `n` and descending to rank `1`, we compute the value of this function for all the squares at each successive rank.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Picking the square that holds the minimum value at each rank gives us the shortest path between rank `n` and rank `1`.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] The function `q(i, j)` is equal to the minimum cost to get to any of the three squares below it (since those are the only squares that can reach it) plus `c(i, j)`.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] The first line of this equation deals with a board modeled as squares indexed on `1` at the lowest bound and `n` at the highest bound.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] The second line specifies what happens at the first rank; providing a base case.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] The third line, the recursion, is the important part.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] It represents the `A,B,C,D` terms in the example.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] From this definition we can derive straightforward recursive code for `q(i, j)`.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] This function only computes the path cost, not the actual path.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] This, like the Fibonacci-numbers example, is horribly slow because it too exhibits the **overlapping sub-problems** attribute.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] That is, it recomputes the same path costs over and over.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] However, we can compute it much faster in a bottom-up fashion if we store path costs in a two-dimensional array `q[i, j]` rather than using a function.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] This avoids recomputation; all the values needed for array `q[i, j]` are computed ahead of time only once.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Precomputed values for `(i,j)` are simply looked up whenever needed.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] We also need to know what the actual shortest path is.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] To do this, we use another array `p[i, j]`; a *predecessor array*.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] This array records the path to any square `s`.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] The predecessor of `s` is modeled as an offset relative to the index (in `q[i, j]`) of the precomputed path cost of `s`.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] To reconstruct the complete path, we lookup the predecessor of `s`, then the predecessor of that square, then the predecessor of that square, and so on recursively, until we reach the starting square.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Now the rest is a simple matter of finding the minimum and printing it.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] In genetics, sequence alignment is an important application where dynamic programming is essential.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Typically, the problem consists of transforming one sequence into another using edit operations that replace, insert, or remove an element.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Each operation has an associated cost, and the goal is to find the sequence of edits with the lowest total cost.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] 3. replacing the first character of A with the first character of B, and performing optimal alignments of the tails of A and B.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] The partial alignments can be tabulated in a matrix, where cell (i,j) contains the cost of the optimal alignment of A[1..i] to B[1..j].
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] The cost in cell (i,j) can be calculated by adding the cost of the relevant operations to the cost of its neighboring cells, and selecting the optimum.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Different variants exist, see Smith–Waterman algorithm and Needleman–Wunsch algorithm.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] The **Tower of Hanoi** or **Towers of Hanoi** is a mathematical game or puzzle.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] It consists of three rods, and a number of disks of different sizes which can slide onto any rod.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] The puzzle starts with the disks in a neat stack in ascending order of size on one rod, the smallest at the top, thus making a conical shape.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] S(n, h, t) := solution to a problem consisting of n disks that are to be moved from rod h to rod t.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] For n=1 the problem is trivial, namely S(1,h,t) = "move a disk from rod h to rod t" (there is only one disk left).
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] The number of moves required by this solution is 2*n* − 1.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] If the objective is to **maximize** the number of moves (without cycling) then the dynamic programming functional equation is slightly more complicated and 3*n* − 1 moves are required.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] A famous puzzle relates to dropping eggs from a building to determine at which height they start to break.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] terminology, in which the first floor is at ground level).
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] If only one egg is available and we wish to be sure of obtaining the right result, the experiment can be carried out in only one way.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Drop the egg from the first-floor window; if it survives, drop it from the second-floor window.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] In the worst case, this method may require 36 droppings.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] What is the lowest number of egg-droppings that is guaranteed to work in all cases?
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] For instance, *s* = (2,6) indicates that two test eggs are available and 6 (consecutive) floors are yet to be tested.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] The initial state of the process is *s* = (*N*,*H*) where *N* denotes the number of test eggs available at the commencement of the experiment.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] The process terminates either when there are no more test eggs (*n* = 0) or when *k* = 0, whichever occurs first.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] If termination occurs at state *s* = (0,*k*) and *k* > 0, then the test failed.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] It is easy to solve this equation iteratively by systematically increasing the values of *n* and *k*.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Notice that the above solution takes $O(nk^{2})$ time with a DP solution.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] This can be improved to $O(nk\log k)$ time by binary searching on the optimal x in the above recurrence, since $W(n-1,x-1)$ is increasing in x while $W(n,k-x)$ is decreasing in x , thus a local minimum of $\max(W(n-1,x-1),W(n,k-x))$ is a global minimum.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Also, by storing the optimal x for each cell in the DP table and referring to its value for the previous cell, the optimal x for each cell can be found in constant time, improving it to $O(nk)$ time.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Let k be the total number of floors such that the eggs break when dropped from the k th floor (The example above is equivalent to taking $k=37$ ).
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Let m be the minimum floor from which the egg must be dropped to be broken.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Let $f(t,n)$ be the maximum number of values of m that are distinguishable using t tries and n eggs.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Let a be the floor from which the first egg is dropped in the optimal strategy.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] If the first egg broke, m is from 1 to a and distinguishable using at most $t-1$ tries and $n-1$ eggs.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] If the first egg did not break, m is from $a+1$ to k and distinguishable using $t-1$ tries and n eggs.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Then the problem is equivalent to finding the minimum x such that $f(x,n)\geq k$ .
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] To do so, we could compute $\{f(t,i):0\leq i\leq n\}$ in order of increasing t , which would take $O(nx)$ time.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Thus, if we separately handle the case of $n=1$ , the algorithm would take $O(n{\sqrt {k}})$ time.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] But the recurrence relation can in fact be solved, giving $f(t,n)=\sum _{i=0}^{n}{\binom {t}{i}}$ , which can be computed in $O(n)$ time using the identity ${\binom {t}{i+1}}={\binom {t}{i}}{\frac {t-i}{i+1}}$ for all $i\geq 0$ .
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Since $f(t,n)\leq f(t+1,n)$ for all $t\geq 0$ , we can binary search on t to find x , giving an $O(n\log k)$ algorithm.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Matrix chain multiplication is a well-known example that demonstrates utility of dynamic programming.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] For example, engineering applications often have to multiply a chain of matrices.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] It is not surprising to find matrices of large dimensions, for example 100×100.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Matrix multiplication is not commutative, but is associative; and we can multiply only two matrices at a time.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] There are numerous ways to multiply this chain of matrices.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] They will all produce the same final result, however they will take more or less time to compute, based on which particular matrices are multiplied.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] If matrix A has dimensions m×n and matrix B has dimensions n×q, then matrix C=A×B will have dimensions m×q, and will require m*n*q scalar multiplications (using a simplistic matrix multiplication algorithm for purposes of illustration).
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] For example, let us multiply matrices A, B and C.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Let us assume that their dimensions are m×n, n×p, and p×s, respectively.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] (A×B)×C This order of matrix multiplication will require mnp + mps scalar calculations.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] So, the first way to multiply the chain will require 1,000,000 + 1,000,000 calculations.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] The second way will require only 10,000 + 100,000 calculations.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Obviously, the second way is faster, and we should multiply the matrices using that arrangement of parenthesis.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Therefore, our conclusion is that the order of parenthesis matters, and that our task is to find the optimal order of parenthesis.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] At this point, we have several choices, one of which is to design a dynamic programming algorithm that will split the problem into overlapping problems and calculate the optimal arrangement of parenthesis.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] The dynamic programming solution is presented below.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Let's call m[i,j] the minimum number of scalar multiplications needed to multiply a chain of matrices from matrix i to matrix j (i.e.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] We split the chain at some matrix k, such that i <= k < j, and try to find out which combination produces minimum m[i,j].
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] So far, we have calculated values for all possible *m*[*i*, *j*], the minimum number of calculations to multiply a chain from matrix *i* to matrix *j*, and we have recorded the corresponding "split point"*s*[*i*, *j*].
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] This algorithm will produce "tables" *m*[, ] and *s*[, ] that will have entries for all possible values of i and j.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] The final solution for the entire chain is m[1, n], with corresponding split at s[1, n].
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Unraveling the solution will be recursive, starting from the top and continuing until we reach the base case, i.e. multiplication of single matrices.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Therefore, the next step is to actually split the chain, i.e. to place the parenthesis where they (optimally) belong.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Of course, this algorithm is not useful for actual multiplication.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] This algorithm is just a user-friendly way to see what the result looks like.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] The term *dynamic programming* was originally used in the 1940s by Richard Bellman to describe the process of solving problems where one needs to find the best decisions one after another.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] By 1953, he refined this to the modern meaning, referring specifically to nesting smaller decision problems inside larger decisions, and the field was thereafter recognized by the IEEE as a systems analysis and engineering topic.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Bellman's contribution is remembered in the name of the Bellman equation, a central result of dynamic programming which restates an optimization problem in recursive form.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] The word *dynamic* was chosen by Bellman to capture the time-varying aspect of the problems, and because it sounded impressive.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] The word *programming* referred to the use of the method to find an optimal *program*, in the sense of a military schedule for training or logistics.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] This usage is the same as that in the phrases *linear programming* and *mathematical programming*, a synonym for mathematical optimization.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] The above explanation of the origin of the term may be inaccurate: According to Russell and Norvig, the above story "cannot be strictly true, because his first paper using the term (Bellman, 1952) appeared before Wilson became Secretary of Defense in 1953." Also, Harold J.
[src:knapsack-dp/dynamic-programming] Kushner stated in a speech that, "On the other hand, when I asked [Bellman] the same question, he replied that he was trying to upstage Dantzig's linear programming by adding dynamic.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] A **greedy algorithm** is an algorithm which, at each step, makes the choice that is locally optimal, and subsequently does not reconsider past choices.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] Greedy algorithms are often used to solve combinatorial optimization problems.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] If an optimization problem only depends on the partial solution of solving it for one subproblem, we can solve this problem by "greedily" considering only the locally optimal subproblem.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] In this sense, a greedy algorithm is a special case of a dynamic programming algorithm.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] In many cases, a greedy algorithm does not produce an exact solution, but can yield solutions that approximate an exact solution in a reasonable amount of time.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] An example of a problem which admits an exact greedy solution, the activity selection problem.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] Given a collection of tasks which can be done between allotted time intervals, the problem is to determine the maximum number of tasks that can be done.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] A greedy algorithm in $O(n\log(n))$ which solves this problem sorts the tasks by the end time and then repeatedly chooses the first task that begins after the last task ended.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] Many classic algorithms in computer science such as the Huffman coding algorithm, Prim's algorithm, Kruskal's algorithm, and Dijkstra's algorithm all use greedy properties in their design.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] Mathematicians frequently use *greedy strategies* in proofs as well.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] A classic example is what Raphael Yuster refers to as the greedy proof that every tournament in graph contains a Hamiltonian path.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] Since there is no formal definition of what a greedy algorithm is, a complete characterization of when a problem admits a greedy algorithm as a solution is not known.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] However, special cases have been identified.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] Jack Edmonds showed that a greedy algorithm can be used to solve a class of linear combinatorial optimization problems with a matroid structure.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] Later Bernhard Korte and László Lovász characterized a broader class of optimization problems by introducing the notion of a greedoid.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] This allowed, for example, a proof of the optimality of Prim's algorithm.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] Algorithms which undo past steps are not greedy.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] For example, the Gale-Shapley algorithm is not a greedy algorithm since although it constructs a solution by choosing the current best pairing, in the process, existing solutions may be modified.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] One technique used to prove the optimiality of greedy algorithms is an exchange argument.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] The exchange argument demonstrates that any solution different from the greedy solution is at most as good as the greedy solution.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] Conclude by induction that the greedy solution is optimal.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] Starting from A, a greedy algorithm that tries to find the maximum by following the greatest slope will find the local maximum at "m", oblivious to the global maximum at "M".
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] To reach the largest sum, at each step, the greedy algorithm will choose what appears to be the optimal immediate choice, so it will choose 12 instead of 3 at the second step, and will not reach the best solution, which contains 99.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] Graph theory is a rich source of greedy algorithms.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] Computing scientists frequently use greedy algorithms frequently to compute graph invariants.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] Greedy algorithms are also used to find upper bounds for the chromatic numbers.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] A simple example is the bound $\chi (G)\leq \Delta (G)+1$ obtained by a greedy algorithm.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] We begin by taking a vertex that has not been colored.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] Since it has at most $\Delta (G)$ neighbours, at most $\Delta (G)$ colors are used in adjacent vertices, leaving a color free for the vertex under consideration.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] A solution to the NP-complete travelling salesman problem can be approximated by starting from an empty edge set and then adding the next cheapest edge which is a subgraph of a complete tour.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] This greedy algorithm has been proven to yield at most $\Theta (\log n)$ times longer than the optimal tour.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] Another example is that a solution for the 0-1 knapsack problem can be approximated by using the greedy algorithm for the fractional knapsack problem.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] This greedy algorithm has been proven to yield a solution at least half the value of the optimal solution.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] Solutions for submodular maximization are approximated using a greedy algorithm which yields a solution at least half the value of the optimal solution.
[src:knapsack-dp/greedy-algorithm] Problems for which greedy algorithms are used to provide approximation algorithms include the set cover, load balancing, Steiner tree and independent set problem.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Given a set of items, each with a weight and a value, determine which items to include in the collection so that the total weight is less than or equal to a given limit and the total value is as large as possible.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] It derives its name from the problem faced by someone who is constrained by a fixed-size knapsack and must fill it with the most valuable items.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] The problem often arises in resource allocation where the decision-makers have to choose from a set of non-divisible projects or tasks under a fixed budget or time constraint, respectively.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] The knapsack problem has been studied for more than a century, with early works dating back to 1897.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] The subset sum problem is a special case of the decision and 0-1 problems where for each kind of item, the weight equals the value: $w_{i}=v_{i}$ .
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] In the field of cryptography, the term *knapsack problem* is often used to refer specifically to the subset sum problem.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] The subset sum problem is one of Karp's 21 NP-complete problems.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] One early application of knapsack algorithms was in the construction and scoring of tests in which the test-takers have a choice as to which questions they answer.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] For small examples, it is a fairly simple process to provide the test-takers with such a choice.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] For example, if an exam contains 12 questions each worth 10 points, the test-taker need only answer 10 questions to achieve a maximum possible score of 100 points.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] However, on tests with a heterogeneous distribution of point values, it is more difficult to provide choices.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Feuerman and Weiss proposed a system in which students are given a heterogeneous test with a total of 125 possible points.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] The students are asked to answer all of the questions to the best of their abilities.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Of the possible subsets of problems whose total point values add up to 100, a knapsack algorithm would determine which subset gives each student the highest possible score.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] The most common problem being solved is the **0-1 knapsack problem**, which restricts the number *$x_{i}$* of copies of each kind of item to zero or one.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Here *$x_{i}$* represents the number of instances of item *i* to include in the knapsack.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Informally, the problem is to maximize the sum of the values of the items in the knapsack so that the sum of the weights is less than or equal to the knapsack's capacity.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] The **unbounded knapsack problem** (**UKP**) places no upper bound on the number of copies of each kind of item and can be formulated as above except that the only restriction on $x_{i}$ is that it is a non-negative integer.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] One example of the unbounded knapsack problem is given using the figure shown at the beginning of this article and the text "if any number of each book is available" in the caption of that figure.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] On the other hand, if an algorithm finds the optimal value of the optimization problem in polynomial time, then the decision problem can be solved in polynomial time by comparing the value of the solution output by this algorithm with the value of k.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Thus, both versions of the problem are of similar difficulty.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] One theme in research literature is to identify what the "hard" instances of the knapsack problem look like, or viewed another way, to identify what properties of instances in practice might make them more amenable than their worst-case NP-complete behaviour suggests.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] The goal in finding these "hard" instances is for their use in public-key cryptography systems, such as the Merkle–Hellman knapsack cryptosystem.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] More generally, better understanding of the structure of the space of instances of an optimization problem helps to advance the study of the particular problem and can improve algorithm selection.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Furthermore, notable is the fact that the hardness of the knapsack problem depends on the form of the input.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] If the weights and profits are given as integers, it is weakly NP-complete, while it is strongly NP-complete if the weights and profits are given as rational numbers.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] However, in the case of rational weights and profits it still admits a fully polynomial-time approximation scheme.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] The NP-hardness of the Knapsack problem relates to computational models in which the size of integers matters (such as the Turing machine).
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] In contrast, decision trees count each decision as a single step.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Dobkin and Lipton show an ${1 \over 2}n^{2}$ lower bound on linear decision trees for the knapsack problem, that is, trees where decision nodes test the sign of affine functions.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] This was generalized to algebraic decision trees by Steele and Yao.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] This model covers more algorithms than the algebraic decision-tree model, as it encompasses algorithms that use indexing into tables.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] However, in this model all program steps are counted, not just decisions.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] An *upper bound* for a decision-tree model was given by Meyer auf der Heide who showed that for every *n* there exists an *O*(*n*4)-deep linear decision tree that solves the subset-sum problem with *n* items.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Note that this does not imply any upper bound for an algorithm that should solve the problem for *any given n*.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Several algorithms are available to solve knapsack problems, based on the dynamic programming approach, the branch and bound approach or hybridizations of both approaches.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] The **unbounded knapsack problem** (**UKP**) places no restriction on the number of copies of each kind of item.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] The second property needs to be explained in detail.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] During the process of the running of this method, how do we get the weight w ?
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] There are only i ways and the previous weights are $w-w_{1},w-w_{2},...,w-w_{i}$ where there are total i kinds of different item (by saying different, we mean that the weight and the value are not completely the same).
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] If we know each value of these i items and the related maximum value previously, we just compare them to each other and get the maximum value ultimately and we are done.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Here the maximum of the empty set is taken to be zero.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Tabulating the results from $m[0]$ up through $m[W]$ gives the solution.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Since the calculation of each $m[w]$ involves examining at most n items, and there are at most W values of $m[w]$ to calculate, the running time of the dynamic programming solution is $O(nW)$ .
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Dividing $w_{1},\,w_{2},\,\ldots ,\,w_{n},\,W$ by their greatest common divisor is a way to improve the running time.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Even if P≠NP, the $O(nW)$ complexity does not contradict the fact that the knapsack problem is NP-complete, since W , unlike n , is not polynomial in the length of the input to the problem.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] The length of the W input to the problem is proportional to the number of bits in W , $\log W$ , not to W itself.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] However, since this runtime is pseudopolynomial, this makes the (decision version of the) knapsack problem a weakly NP-complete problem.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] A similar dynamic programming solution for the 0-1 knapsack problem also runs in pseudo-polynomial time.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Define $m[i,w]$ to be the maximum value that can be attained with weight less than or equal to w using items up to i (first i items).
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] The solution can then be found by calculating $m[n,W]$ .
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] To do this efficiently, we can use a table to store previous computations.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] This solution will therefore run in $O(nW)$ time and $O(nW)$ space.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] However, if we take it a step or two further, we should know that the method will run in the time between $O(nW)$ and $O(2^{n})$ .
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] From **Definition A**, we know that there is no need to compute all the weights when the number of items and the items themselves that we chose are fixed.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] That is to say, the program above computes more than necessary because the weight changes from 0 to W often.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] From this perspective, we can program this method so that it runs recursively.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] For example, there are 10 different items and the weight limit is 67.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Besides, we can break the recursion and convert it into a tree.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Then we can cut some leaves and use parallel computing to expedite the running of this method.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Another algorithm for 0-1 knapsack, discovered in 1974 and sometimes called "meet-in-the-middle" due to parallels to a similarly named algorithm in cryptography, is exponential in the number of different items but may be preferable to the DP algorithm when W is large compared to *n*.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] As with the meet in the middle attack in cryptography, this improves on the $O(n2^{n})$ runtime of a naive brute force approach (examining all subsets of $\{1...n\}$ ), at the cost of using exponential rather than constant space (see also baby-step giant-step).
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] In contrast, the best known deterministic algorithm runs in $O^{*}(2^{n/2})$ time with a slightly worse space complexity of $O^{*}(2^{n/4})$ .
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] As for most NP-complete problems, it may be enough to find workable solutions even if they are not optimal.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Preferably, however, the approximation comes with a guarantee of the difference between the value of the solution found and the value of the optimal solution.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] As with many useful but computationally complex algorithms, there has been substantial research on creating and analyzing algorithms that approximate a solution.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] The knapsack problem, though NP-Hard, is one of a collection of algorithms that can still be approximated to any specified degree.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] This means that the problem has a polynomial time approximation scheme.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] To be exact, the knapsack problem has a fully polynomial time approximation scheme (FPTAS).
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] George Dantzig proposed a greedy approximation algorithm to solve the unbounded knapsack problem.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] His version sorts the items in decreasing order of value per unit of weight, $v_{1}/w_{1}\geq \cdots \geq v_{n}/w_{n}$ .
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] It then proceeds to insert them into the sack, starting with as many copies as possible of the first kind of item until there is no longer space in the sack for more.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Provided that there is an unlimited supply of each kind of item, if m is the maximum value of items that fit into the sack, then the greedy algorithm is guaranteed to achieve at least a value of $m/2$ .
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] For the bounded problem, where the supply of each kind of item is limited, the above algorithm may be far from optimal.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Nevertheless, a simple modification allows us to solve this case: Assume for simplicity that all items individually fit in the sack ( $w_{i}\leq W$ for all i ).
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Construct a solution $S_{1}$ by packing items greedily as long as possible, i.e. $S_{1}=\left\{1,\ldots ,k\right\}$ where $k=\textstyle \max _{1\leq k'\leq n}\textstyle \sum _{i=1}^{k'}w_{i}\leq W$ .
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Furthermore, construct a second solution $S_{2}=\left\{k+1\right\}$ containing the first item that did not fit.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Since $S_{1}\cup S_{2}$ provides an upper bound for the LP relaxation of the problem, one of the sets must have value at least $m/2$ ; we thus return whichever of $S_{1}$ and $S_{2}$ has better value to obtain a $1/2$ -approximation.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] The fully polynomial time approximation scheme (FPTAS) for the knapsack problem takes advantage of the fact that the reason the problem has no known polynomial time solutions is because the profits associated with the items are not restricted.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] If one rounds off some of the least significant digits of the profit values then they will be bounded by a polynomial and 1/ε where ε is a bound on the correctness of the solution.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] This restriction then means that an algorithm can find a solution in polynomial time that is correct within a factor of (1-ε) of the optimal solution.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Quantum approximate optimization algorithm (QAOA) can be employed to solve Knapsack problem using quantum computation by minimizing the Hamiltonian of the problem.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] The Knapsack Hamiltonian is constructed via embedding the constraint condition to the cost function of the problem with a penalty term. ${H}=-\sum _{i=1}^{n}v_{i}x_{i}+P\left(\sum _{i=1}^{n}w_{i}x_{i}-W\right)^{2},$ where P is the penalty constant which is determined by case-specific fine-tuning.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Solving the unbounded knapsack problem can be made easier by throwing away items which will never be needed.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] For a given item i , suppose we could find a set of items J such that their total weight is less than the weight of i , and their total value is greater than the value of i .
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Then i cannot appear in the optimal solution, because we could always improve any potential solution containing i by replacing i with the set J .
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Therefore, we can disregard the i -th item altogether.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] In such cases, J is said to **dominate** i .
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Finding dominance relations allows us to significantly reduce the size of the search space.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] The vector x denotes the number of copies of each member of J .
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Verifying this dominance is computationally hard, so it can only be used with a dynamic programming approach.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] This dominance could be efficiently used during preprocessing because it can be detected relatively easily.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] This is the item with the greatest density of value.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] There are many variations of the knapsack problem that have arisen from the vast number of applications of the basic problem.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] The main variations occur by changing the number of some problem parameter such as the number of items, number of objectives, or even the number of knapsacks.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Here, instead of a single objective (e.g. maximizing the monetary profit from the items in the knapsack), there can be several objectives.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] For example, there could be environmental or social concerns as well as economic goals.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Problems frequently addressed include portfolio and transportation logistics optimizations.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] As an example, suppose you run a cruise ship.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] You have to decide how many famous comedians to hire.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] This boat can handle no more than one ton of passengers and the entertainers must weigh less than 1000 lbs.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Each comedian has a weight, brings in business based on their popularity and asks for a specific salary.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] In this example, you have multiple objectives.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] You want, of course, to maximize the popularity of your entertainers while minimizing their salaries.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Also, you want to have as many entertainers as possible.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Here, the weight of knapsack item i is given by a D-dimensional vector ${\overline {w_{i}}}=(w_{i1},\ldots ,w_{iD})$ and the knapsack has a D-dimensional capacity vector $(W_{1},\ldots ,W_{D})$ .
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] The target is to maximize the sum of the values of the items in the knapsack so that the sum of weights in each dimension d does not exceed $W_{d}$ .
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Multi-dimensional knapsack is computationally harder than knapsack; even for $D=2$ , the problem does not have EPTAS unless P = NP.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] However, the algorithm in is shown to solve sparse instances efficiently.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] An instance of multi-dimensional knapsack is sparse if there is a set $J=\{1,2,\ldots ,m\}$ for $m<D$ such that for every knapsack item i , $\exists z>m$ such that $\forall j\in J\cup \{z\},\ w_{ij}\geq 0$ and $\forall y\notin J\cup \{z\},w_{iy}=0$ .
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Such instances occur, for example, when scheduling packets in a wireless network with relay nodes.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] The algorithm from also solves sparse instances of the multiple choice variant, multiple-choice multi-dimensional knapsack.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] The IHS (Increasing Height Shelf) algorithm is optimal for 2D knapsack (packing squares into a two-dimensional unit size square): when there are at most five squares in an optimal packing.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] This may seem like a trivial change, but it is not equivalent to adding to the capacity of the initial knapsack, as each knapsack has its own capacity constraint.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] This variation is used in many loading and scheduling problems in Operations Research and has a Polynomial-time approximation scheme.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] This variation is similar to the Bin Packing Problem.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] It differs from the Bin Packing Problem in that a subset of items can be selected, whereas, in the Bin Packing Problem, all items have to be packed to certain bins.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] The **quadratic knapsack problem** maximizes a quadratic objective function subject to binary and linear capacity constraints.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] The problem was introduced by Gallo, Hammer, and Simeone in 1980, however the first treatment of the problem dates back to Witzgall in 1975.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] In the **geometric knapsack problem**, there is a set of rectangles with different values, and a rectangular knapsack.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] The goal is to pack the largest possible value into the knapsack.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] In the **online knapsack problem**, the items come one by one.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Whenever an item arrives, we must decide immediately whether to put it in the knapsack or discard it.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] There are two variants: (a) non-removable - an inserted item remains in the knapsack forever; (b) removable - an inserted item may be removed later, to make room for a new item.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] Han, Kawase and Makino present a randomized algorithm for the unweighted non-removable setting.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] It is 2-competitive, which is the best possible.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] For the weighted removable setting, they give a 2-competitive algorithm, prove a lower bound of ~1.368 for randomized algorithms, and prove that no deterministic algorithm can have a constant competitive ratio.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] For the unweighted removable setting, they give an 10/7-competitive-ratio algorithm, and prove a lower bound of 1.25.
[src:knapsack-dp/knapsack-problem] There are several other papers on the online knapsack problem.
[src:knapsack-dp/optimal-substructure] In computer science, a problem is said to have **optimal substructure** if an optimal solution can be constructed from optimal solutions of its subproblems.
[src:knapsack-dp/optimal-substructure] This property is used to determine the usefulness of greedy algorithms for a problem.
[src:knapsack-dp/optimal-substructure] Typically, a greedy algorithm is used to solve a problem with optimal substructure if it can be proven by induction that this is optimal at each step.
[src:knapsack-dp/optimal-substructure] Otherwise, provided the problem exhibits overlapping subproblems as well, divide-and-conquer methods or dynamic programming may be used.
[src:knapsack-dp/optimal-substructure] If there are no appropriate greedy algorithms and the problem fails to exhibit overlapping subproblems, often a lengthy but straightforward search of the solution space is the best alternative.
[src:knapsack-dp/optimal-substructure] This is an example of optimal substructure.
[src:knapsack-dp/optimal-substructure] The Principle of Optimality is used to derive the Bellman equation, which shows how the value of the problem starting from *t* is related to the value of the problem starting from *s*.
[src:knapsack-dp/optimal-substructure] Consider finding a shortest path for traveling between two cities by car, as illustrated in Figure 1.
[src:knapsack-dp/optimal-substructure] Such an example is likely to exhibit optimal substructure.
[src:knapsack-dp/optimal-substructure] That is, if the shortest route from Seattle to Los Angeles passes through Portland and then Sacramento, then the shortest route from Portland to Los Angeles must pass through Sacramento too.
[src:knapsack-dp/optimal-substructure] That is, the problem of how to get from Portland to Los Angeles is nested inside the problem of how to get from Seattle to Los Angeles.
[src:knapsack-dp/optimal-substructure] As an example of a problem that is unlikely to exhibit optimal substructure, consider the problem of finding the cheapest airline ticket from Buenos Aires to Moscow.
[src:knapsack-dp/optimal-substructure] A slightly more formal definition of optimal substructure can be given.
[src:knapsack-dp/optimal-substructure] Let a "problem" be a collection of "alternatives", and let each alternative have an associated cost, *c*(*a*).
[src:knapsack-dp/optimal-substructure] The task is to find a set of alternatives that minimizes *c*(*a*).
[src:knapsack-dp/optimal-substructure] Suppose that the alternatives can be partitioned into subsets, i.e. each alternative belongs to only one subset.
[src:knapsack-dp/optimal-substructure] Suppose each subset has its own cost function.
[src:knapsack-dp/optimal-substructure] The minima of each of these cost functions can be found, as can the minima of the global cost function, *restricted to the same subsets*.
[src:knapsack-dp/optimal-substructure] If these minima match for each subset, then it's almost obvious that a global minimum can be picked not out of the full set of alternatives, but out of only the set that consists of the minima of the smaller, local cost functions we have defined.
[src:knapsack-dp/optimal-substructure] If minimizing the local functions is a problem of "lower order", and (specifically) if, after a finite number of these reductions, the problem becomes trivial, then the problem has an optimal substructure.
[src:knapsack-dp/overlapping-subproblems] In computer science, a problem is said to have **overlapping subproblems** if the problem can be broken down into subproblems which are reused several times or a recursive algorithm for the problem solves the same subproblem over and over rather than always generating new subproblems.
[src:knapsack-dp/overlapping-subproblems] For example, the problem of computing the Fibonacci sequence exhibits overlapping subproblems.
[src:knapsack-dp/overlapping-subproblems] The problem of computing the *n*th Fibonacci number *F*(*n*), can be broken down into the subproblems of computing *F*(*n* − 1) and *F*(*n* − 2), and then adding the two.
[src:knapsack-dp/overlapping-subproblems] The subproblem of computing *F*(*n* − 1) can itself be broken down into a subproblem that involves computing *F*(*n* − 2).
[src:knapsack-dp/overlapping-subproblems] Therefore, the computation of *F*(*n* − 2) is reused, and the Fibonacci sequence thus exhibits overlapping subproblems.
[src:knapsack-dp/overlapping-subproblems] A naive recursive approach to such a problem generally fails due to an exponential complexity.
[src:knapsack-dp/overlapping-subproblems] If the problem also shares an optimal substructure property, dynamic programming is a good way to work it out.
[src:knapsack-dp/overlapping-subproblems] In the following two implementations for calculating fibonacci sequence, `fibonacci` uses regular recursion and `fibonacci_mem` uses memoization.
[src:knapsack-dp/overlapping-subproblems] `fibonacci_mem` is much more efficient as the value for any particular `n` is computed only once.
[src:knapsack-dp/overlapping-subproblems] The difference in performance may appear minimal with an `n` value of 5; however, as `n` increases, the computational complexity of the original `fibonacci` function grows exponentially.
[src:knapsack-dp/overlapping-subproblems] In contrast, the `fibonacci_mem` version exhibits a more linear increase in complexity.
